A possible reaction mechanism is proposed in Fig. 3d. First, the electrons in the valence band of Bi2O3 are excited to the conduction band after light excitation, thus leaving holes on the valence band. Here, the CQDs adhered to the surface of Bi2O3 sample act as electron acceptors and reservoirs, which are advantageous for the electron transfer process from the conduction band of Bi2O3 to CQDs, thus, inhibiting the recombination of the photogenerated electrons and holes in Bi2O3 bulk (Process I). Then, the electrons further react with oxygen to form superoxide anion radicals O2
                     − (Process III). Instantaneously, the photogenerated holes in the valance band react with water molecules (H2O) to produce the active hydroxyl radicals (OH

                     ). Hence, it can be concluded that the utilization of light for all the composites is greatly enhanced, which matches well with the results of UV–vis diffuse reflectance spectra.
